\/14_hw_sonarC.gif\\\\\\\" alt=\\\\\\\"http:\\\\/\\\\/cdn.artofproblemsolving.com\\\\/school\\\\/crypt\\\\/00001-239f27f2bf6a828fc7e79586847ec339dcd50ccb\\\\/files\\\\/14_hw_sonarC.gif\\\\\\\">\\\"],\\\"areDraggablesReusable\\\":false,\\\"height\\\":600},\\\"problem_text_fmt\\\":\\\"\\\\tThe speed of sound in the upper part of the ocean changes dramatically based on geography, season, weather, and more. Down to a depth of a few hundred meters, the speed of sound can increase, decrease, or remain approximately constant. The three possibilities have very different ramifications for the path of sound in the water.<br>\\\\n<br>\\\\nSonar operators must be aware of local conditions, so they know what path the original and reflected waves are taking.<br>\\\\n<br>\\\\n<b>Match each diagram of sonar paths leaving a boat with the correct graph of speed of sound versus depth.<\\\\/b><br>\\\\n\\\"}\"}]",
 "solution_text": "Here is the correct arrangement:\\n\\n[img]http://cdn.artofproblemsolving.com/school/crypt/00001-239f27f2bf6a828fc7e79586847ec339dcd50ccb/files/14_hw_sub_sonar_soln.png[/img]\\n\\nIf the speed of sound is constant with depth, there is no refraction. The paths remain straight.\\n\\nIf the speed of sound decreases with depth, then sound waves moving downward will slow down. In that case, the path bends towards the normal. That's the downward-curving paths.\\n\\nIf the speed of sound increases with depth, then sounds moving downward will speed up. The path bends away from the normal, which is the upward curving paths."
